### Image Formats Explained — WebP, AVIF, srcset, Tools

#### What is WebP? When is it useful?

**WebP** is a modern image format created by Google.

- **What it does:** Compresses images smaller than JPEG/PNG while keeping the same visual quality
- **How much smaller:** ~25–40% smaller than JPEG, ~25% smaller than PNG
- **Supports:** Lossy compression, lossless, and transparency (JPEG doesn't support transparency)
- **Browser support:** All modern browsers — Chrome, Firefox, Safari 14+, Edge

**When to use it:**
- Use WebP for ALL photos, product images, banners, thumbnails on any website
- If you're serving a 500KB JPEG today, WebP makes it ~300KB — no quality loss visible to user
- It is the current standard. There is almost no reason to use JPEG/PNG for web images anymore.

```html
<!-- Use <picture> to serve WebP with JPEG fallback for very old browsers -->
<picture>
  <source srcset="hero.webp" type="image/webp" />
  <img src="hero.jpg" alt="Hero image" width="1200" height="600" />
</picture>
```

#### What is AVIF? When is it useful?

**AVIF** is an even newer format based on the AV1 video codec.

- **How much smaller:** ~50% smaller than JPEG, ~20% smaller than WebP
- **Best for:** High-quality photos and illustrations with gradients
- **Browser support:** Chrome 85+, Firefox 93+, Safari 16+ — not universal yet
- **Encoding:** AVIF encoding is slower (build time) and not all CDNs support it yet

**When to prefer WebP over AVIF:** For most production apps today, WebP is the sweet spot — widely supported, fast to encode, significant compression gains.

```html
<!-- Serve AVIF first, WebP as fallback, JPEG as last resort -->
<picture>
  <source srcset="hero.avif" type="image/avif" />
  <source srcset="hero.webp" type="image/webp" />
  <img src="hero.jpg" alt="Hero" width="1200" height="600" />
</picture>
```

#### What is `srcset`? When is it useful?

**Problem it solves:** Without `srcset`, a mobile phone with a 375px screen downloads the same 2000px image as a desktop monitor. That's downloading 5x more image data than needed — pure waste.

**`srcset` tells the browser: "here are multiple sizes of this image — pick the right one for the current device."**

```html
<img
  src="img-800.webp"
  srcset="img-400.webp 400w, img-800.webp 800w, img-1600.webp 1600w"
  sizes="(max-width: 600px) 400px, (max-width: 1200px) 800px, 1600px"
  loading="lazy"
  width="800"
  height="400"
  alt="Product image"
/>
```

- `400w` — this image file is 400px wide
- `sizes` — at this viewport width, the image renders at this CSS size
- Browser picks the smallest image that is still large enough — automatically

**When is it useful:** Any time you have images that display at different sizes on different screen sizes — which is basically every website.

#### Tools for image optimization — what each one is

| Tool | What it is | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| **Squoosh** (squoosh.app) | Google's browser-based image compressor. Drag and drop an image, pick output format, compare quality side by side. | Manual one-off conversion. Testing how much quality you lose at different compression levels. |
| **sharp** (npm package) | Node.js library for image processing and format conversion. Extremely fast (C++ under the hood). | Automate WebP/AVIF conversion in your build pipeline or Express upload handler. |
| **imagemin** | Webpack/Vite plugin. Converts and compresses images automatically during build. | Auto-optimize all images in `/public` folder on every build — zero manual effort. |
| **Cloudinary** | Cloud image CDN. Stores original image, serves optimized version on the fly. Detects browser support and serves WebP or AVIF automatically. | When you have user-uploaded images or a large image library. No manual conversion needed. |
| **Cloudflare Images** | Similar to Cloudinary. Resizes, compresses, and converts on the edge. | When already on Cloudflare — cheapest option for auto image optimization. |
| **Next.js `<Image>` component** | Built-in React component. Auto-lazy loads, generates srcset, serves WebP, prevents CLS. | Any Next.js project — replaces `<img>` entirely. Zero config. |

> **Interview answer:** "In production I use Cloudinary or Cloudflare to auto-convert and serve the right format per browser. I don't maintain multiple image files manually — the CDN handles format negotiation via the Accept header."

