## 3. Frontend — JavaScript

### Code Splitting vs Lazy Loading — Clear Difference

> This is the most commonly confused concept in front-end performance interviews.

#### Code Splitting

**What it is:** Breaking your single large JS bundle into multiple smaller chunks at **build time**, so the browser only downloads what's needed for the current page.

**Key point:** Code splitting is about HOW the bundle is divided. It happens at the **bundler level** (Webpack, Vite, Rollup). The output is multiple `.js` files instead of one.

**Without code splitting:**
```
dist/
  bundle.js  →  3.2MB  ← contains ALL routes (home + dashboard + settings + admin)

User visits /home → must download all 3.2MB even though home needs only 200KB
```

**With code splitting:**
```
dist/
  home.chunk.js        →  200KB
  dashboard.chunk.js   →  400KB
  settings.chunk.js    →  150KB
  vendor.chunk.js      →  900KB  ← React, lodash (cached separately, rarely changes)

User visits /home → downloads home.chunk.js (200KB) + vendor.chunk.js (from cache)
```

#### Lazy Loading

**What it is:** Deferring the **loading request** to a resource (component, image, module) until it is actually needed at **runtime** — when the user navigates to a route, opens a modal, or an image enters the viewport.

**Key point:** Lazy loading is about WHEN the resource is fetched. It happens in the browser at runtime.

#### The relationship between them

Code splitting creates the separate chunks.
Lazy loading decides when to download those chunks.

> **Pizza analogy:** Code splitting = cutting the pizza into slices. Lazy loading = only picking up a slice when you're ready to eat it. You need both — slicing alone doesn't help if you still eat the whole pizza at once.

#### Side-by-side comparison

| | Code Splitting | Lazy Loading |
|---|---|---|
| **What** | Divides bundle into smaller chunks | Delays fetching a resource until needed |
| **When** | At build time (bundler) | At runtime (browser) |
| **Tool** | Webpack / Vite config, `manualChunks` | `React.lazy()`, dynamic `import()`, `loading="lazy"` |
| **Applies to** | JavaScript modules and routes | Components, images, routes, any module |
| **Result** | Smaller initial download | Resources load on demand |
| **Works alone?** | Yes, but files still downloaded eagerly | Yes (e.g. image `loading="lazy"`) |
| **Best together?** | Route splitting + lazy load = smallest initial JS + on-demand fetch |

---

### Code Splitting Techniques

#### 1. Route-based splitting (biggest impact, start here)

Split the bundle per route — one chunk per page. Most impactful technique.

```jsx
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';

const Home      = lazy(() => import('./pages/Home'));
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Settings  = lazy(() => import('./pages/Settings'));
const Admin     = lazy(() => import('./pages/Admin'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<PageSpinner />}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/"          element={<Home />} />
        <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
        <Route path="/settings"  element={<Settings />} />
        <Route path="/admin"     element={<Admin />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

Vite and Webpack automatically create separate chunk files for each `import()`.

#### 2. Component-based splitting (for heavy components not immediately visible)

Modals, sidebars, charts, rich text editors — things that load only on user action.

```jsx
const HeavyChartModal = lazy(() => import('./HeavyChartModal'));

function Dashboard() {
  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);
  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setOpen(true)}>View Chart</button>
      {open && (
        <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
          <HeavyChartModal onClose={() => setOpen(false)} />
        </Suspense>
      )}
    </>
  );
}
// HeavyChartModal + its dependencies (chart.js etc.) are only downloaded when user clicks
```

#### 3. Vendor chunk splitting (separate third-party libraries)

Third-party libraries change rarely — split them into their own chunk so users get them from cache on return visits.

```js
// vite.config.js
export default {
  build: {
    rollupOptions: {
      output: {
        manualChunks: {
          vendor: ['react', 'react-dom', 'react-router-dom'],
          charts: ['recharts'],
          utils:  ['lodash', 'date-fns'],
        }
      }
    }
  }
};
```

Now `vendor.chunk.js` is cached forever (or until you update React) — it doesn't re-download when your app code changes.

#### 4. Dynamic import on user action (load library only when needed)

```js
// BAD — chart.js (500KB) loads on page load even if user never views chart
import Chart from 'chart.js';

// GOOD — only loads when user clicks "Show Chart"
async function handleShowChart() {
  const { Chart } = await import('chart.js');
  new Chart(canvasRef.current, config);
}
```

#### 5. Prefetch on hover (smart preloading — feels instant)

Start downloading the next chunk before the user clicks — the download finishes by the time they click.

```jsx
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));

function NavLink() {
  const prefetch = () => import('./Dashboard'); // triggers download silently

  return (
    <Link to="/dashboard" onMouseEnter={prefetch}>
      Dashboard
    </Link>
  );
}
```

#### 6. Webpack Magic Comments

Control chunk naming and priority behavior:

```js
// Named chunk — easier to debug in bundle analyzer
import(/* webpackChunkName: "user-profile" */ './UserProfile');

// Prefetch — downloaded in browser idle time, low priority
import(/* webpackPrefetch: true */ './Dashboard');

// Preload — downloaded immediately with high priority (use sparingly)
import(/* webpackPreload: true */ './HeroSection');
```

