## 5. Backend — Node.js / Express

### Event Loop Protection

```js
// BAD — blocks event loop, no other requests can be served while this runs
const data = fs.readFileSync('large-file.txt');

// GOOD — async, event loop free to handle other requests while waiting
const data = await fs.promises.readFile('large-file.txt');
```

CPU-bound tasks (image processing, PDF generation, complex computation) → Worker Threads:
```js
const { Worker } = require('worker_threads');
const worker = new Worker('./pdf-generator.js', { workerData: payload });
worker.on('message', result => res.json(result));
```

### Clustering

```js
const cluster = require('cluster');
const os = require('os');

if (cluster.isPrimary) {
  os.cpus().forEach(() => cluster.fork());
  cluster.on('exit', () => cluster.fork()); // restart dead workers automatically
} else {
  require('./server'); // each worker is an independent Express app
}
```

Or use **PM2**: `pm2 start server.js -i max` — spawns one worker per CPU core automatically.

### Streams for Large Data

```js
// BAD — loads entire file into memory before sending
app.get('/report', async (req, res) => {
  const data = await fs.promises.readFile('./large-report.csv'); // memory spike
  res.send(data);
});

// GOOD — streams directly to client, constant low memory usage
app.get('/report', (req, res) => {
  const stream = fs.createReadStream('./large-report.csv');
  stream.pipe(res);
});
```

### Express Middleware

```js
const compression = require('compression');
app.use(compression({ level: 6, threshold: 1024 })); // gzip responses > 1KB
```

### Connection Pooling

```js
// Mongoose pools connections automatically
mongoose.connect(URI, { maxPoolSize: 10 }); // reuse 10 connections, don't open new one per request
```

