## 6. Database — MongoDB

### Indexing

```js
db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 });               // single field
db.orders.createIndex({ userId: 1, status: 1 });  // compound (order matters)
db.products.createIndex({ name: "text" });         // full-text search
```

Always verify with explain:
```js
db.users.find({ email: "x@y.com" }).explain("executionStats");
// Look for:
//   stage: "IXSCAN"   → index used (good)
//   stage: "COLLSCAN" → full scan (missing index — add one)
//   executionTimeMillis → actual query time
```

### Query Optimization

```js
// Project — only return fields the client needs
User.findById(id).select('name email avatar').lean();

// .lean() — returns plain JS object not Mongoose Document → 3-5x faster

// Cursor-based pagination (better than skip for large datasets)
Model.find({ _id: { $gt: lastId } }).limit(20).lean();
```

### Aggregation Pipeline

```js
Order.aggregate([
  { $match: { status: 'completed' } },  // filter FIRST — reduces documents early
  { $group: { _id: '$userId', total: { $sum: '$amount' } } },
  { $sort: { total: -1 } },
  { $limit: 10 }
]);
// Process data inside MongoDB, not in Node.js
```

### Schema Design

- **Embed** for 1:few, frequently-accessed-together data (user + address)
- **Reference** for 1:many or large growing sub-documents (user → orders)
- Never let arrays grow unboundedly inside a document

