## 7. API Optimization — Deep Dive

### Identify the Category of Slowness First

| Symptom | Root cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| All endpoints slow | Server under-resourced or event loop blocked | Cluster, scale up |
| One specific endpoint slow | Slow DB query | Index, projection, pipeline |
| Fast first hit, slow after | Cache warming | Add Redis cache |
| Slow under high load | No connection pooling | Pool DB connections |
| Large response payload | Over-fetching | Projection, pagination, GraphQL |
| Many API calls for one page load | Chatty API design | Batch endpoint, BFF pattern |
| Mobile slower than desktop | Same heavy payload for all clients | Field filtering, BFF |

---

### Measure API Performance First

**Log response times in development:**
```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const start = Date.now();
  res.on('finish', () => {
    const duration = Date.now() - start;
    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.path} → ${res.statusCode} [${duration}ms]`);
    if (duration > 500) console.warn(`SLOW: ${req.path} took ${duration}ms`);
  });
  next();
});
```

**In production — use APM (Datadog / New Relic / Sentry):**
- See p95 and p99 latency per endpoint — not average (average hides outliers)
- Trace exactly where time is spent: app code vs DB query vs external API call
- Set alerts on p95 > 500ms

