### 1. Reduce Response Payload

**Projection — never send more than the client needs:**
```js
// User list page only needs name + avatar + role
router.get('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const users = await User.find({})
    .select('name avatar role')
    .lean(); // plain object, no Mongoose overhead
  res.json(users);
});
```

**Field filtering via query params:**
```
GET /api/users?fields=name,email,role
```
```js
const fields = req.query.fields?.split(',').join(' ') || '';
const users = await User.find({}).select(fields).lean();
```

---

### 2. Pagination — Always

**Offset-based (simple, good for small datasets):**
```js
const page  = parseInt(req.query.page)  || 1;
const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit) || 20;
const skip  = (page - 1) * limit;

const [data, total] = await Promise.all([
  Model.find({}).skip(skip).limit(limit).lean(),
  Model.countDocuments()
]);

res.json({ data, total, page, pages: Math.ceil(total / limit) });
```

**Cursor-based (better for large, real-time datasets):**
```js
// Client sends: ?cursor=<lastDocumentId>
const cursor = req.query.cursor;
const query  = cursor ? { _id: { $gt: mongoose.Types.ObjectId(cursor) } } : {};

const data = await Model.find(query).limit(20).lean();
const nextCursor = data.length === 20 ? data[data.length - 1]._id : null;

res.json({ data, nextCursor });
```

> Cursor-based stays fast at page 10,000. Offset-based with `skip(200000)` scans 200,000 documents and is slow.

